1429","1396–1452":"1396–1452","1400–1492":"1400–1492","1426–1465":"1426–1465","1345–1399":"1345–1399","1354–Female":"1354–Overleden","1374":"1374","1396":"1396","1492":"1492","1426":"1426","about 1426":"circa 1426","1345":"1345","1400":"1400","1399":"1399","1465":"1465","1354":"1354","1452":"1452","1375":"1375","about 1396":"circa 1396","1429":"1429","Upminster, Essex, England":"Upminster, Essex, England","White Notley, Essex, England, United Kingdom":"White Notley, Essex, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England","White Notley, Essex, England":"White Notley, Essex, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Essex, England":"Essex, England"},"en":{"about 1396–1429":"about 1396–1429","1375–1400":"1375–1400","1396–1429":"1396–1429","1396–1452":"1396–1452","1400–1492":"1400–1492","1426–1465":"1426–1465","1345–1399":"1345–1399","1354–Female":"1354–Deceased","1374":"1374","1396":"1396","1492":"1492","1426":"1426","about 1426":"about 1426","1345":"1345","1400":"1400","1399":"1399","1465":"1465","1354":"1354","1452":"1452","1375":"1375","about 1396":"about 1396","1429":"1429","Upminster, Essex, England":"Upminster, Essex, England","White Notley, Essex, England, United Kingdom":"White Notley, Essex, England, United Kingdom","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England","White Notley, Essex, England":"White Notley, Essex, England, United Kingdom","Essex, England":"Essex, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Whitebread","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Kent and Middlesex): from Middle English <i>whit bred</i> (Old English <i>hwīt brēad</i> ‘white bread’), probably denoting a baker or seller of white bread. White bread, considered the best bread, was made from wheat flour. The name may also derive from Middle English <i>whete bred</i> ‘wheat bread’ (Old English <i>hwǣte brēad</i>), denoting a baker or seller of bread made from wheat. The terms ‘white bread’ and ‘wheat bread’, though of different origin but with identical reference, fell together. Alternatively, the surname may also derive from a metathesized form of <i>Whitberd</i>, from Middle English <i>whīt</i> ‘white’ + <i>berd</i> ‘beard’ (Old English <i>hwīt</i> + <i>beard</i>), a nickname for someone with a white beard.","In some instances, perhaps an Americanized form (translation into English) of the German cognate   Weisbrot  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Weisbrot","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Baruch, Ari, Shalom.  German Erna.","Jewish (Ashkenazic): variant of   Weisbrod  ."]},{"name":"Whitmill","meanings":["English (Oxfordshire and Northamptonshire): occupational name from the recorded Middle English compound <i>whete-mele</i>, from <i>whete</i> ‘wheat’ + <i>mele</i> ‘meal, flour’, perhaps denoting a miller who ground wheat flour or someone who baked or sold white bread. Compare   Whitebread  . Alternatively, the surname could be a topographic name from Middle English <i>whit</i> ‘white’ + <i>milne</i> ‘mill’, for a person who lived at a place described or named in this way, but no place with this name has been identified."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Thomas Whitebread was born about 1396, in Essex, England, his father, Lord John Christopher Whitbread, was 52 and his mother, Dorothy Jean Bauer, was 43. He had at least 1 daughter with Lady Agnes Hunt. He died in 1429, in Suffolk, England, at the age of 34."},"et":{"about 1396–1429":"umbes 1396–1429","13